The earliest attestation is found in {{w|Robert Morrison (missionary)|Robert Morrison}}'s ''{{w|A Dictionary of the Chinese Language}}'' ({{zh-ref|Zhang, 2016}}).

There are various proposals regarding the etymology of the word:
* From Old Chinese:
** From {{och-l|釜|pot; cauldron}} ({{zh-ref|Chan, 1995}}; {{zh-ref|Xu, 2002}});
** From {{och-l|鍑|pot; cauldron}} ({{w|Zhang Taiyan}}'s ''Xin Fangyan'');
** From {{och-l|缶|earthen jar}} ({{zh-ref|Pan, 2016}});
** From {{och-l|缹|to cook}} ({{zh-ref|Kong, 1933}}).
* From a word in the language of the natives in Lingnan, recorded in {{w2|zh|s:北戶錄|北戶錄|pref=《|suf=》}} as {{ltc-l|褒}} (as in {{lang|zh|褒牛頭}}) ({{zh-ref|Luo, 1960}}; {{zh-ref|Huang, 2011}}).
* From {{bor|zh|en|boil}} ({{zh-ref|Zhang, 2016}}).

